1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,467
D.B. Norton does things
in a much bigger way.

2
00:00:00,628 --> 00:00:03,994
It's his opening attack on you,
Governor. Take my word for it.

3
00:00:04,158 --> 00:00:06,039
What did he buy a paper for?

4
00:00:06,202 --> 00:00:08,517
Why did he engage a
high pressure editor like Connell?

5
00:00:08,689 --> 00:00:12,053
He's in the oil business.
Governor, he's after your scalp.

6
00:00:12,217 --> 00:00:15,500
Alright, Jim.
Don't burst a blood vessel.

7
00:00:15,665 --> 00:00:18,026
- I'll look into it.
- Yes, sir?

8
00:00:18,192 --> 00:00:20,870
Get me Spencer
of the Daily Chronicle, please.

9
00:00:21,038 --> 00:00:24,882
Yes, I saw it, Governor.
If you ask me, it's a phony letter.

10
00:00:25,048 --> 00:00:27,043
That gag's got whiskers on it.

11
00:00:28,055 --> 00:00:31,259
I'll get the Mayor and Chamber
of Commerce to go after them.

12
00:00:31,703 --> 00:00:33,461
Get Mayor Lovett on the phone.

13
00:00:33,630 --> 00:00:35,943
Sorry, the Mayor's busy
on the other phone.

14
00:00:36,115 --> 00:00:39,113
Yes, I know, Mrs. Brewster, it's
a terrible reflection on our city.

15
00:00:39,282 --> 00:00:42,406
- I've had a dozen calls already.
- Spencer at the Chronicle.

16
00:00:42,570 --> 00:00:43,483
Just a minute.

17
00:00:43,653 --> 00:00:45,328
Yes, Mrs. Brewster, I'm listening.

18
00:00:45,497 --> 00:00:49,385
I insist that this John Doe
be found a job at once.

19
00:00:49,546 --> 00:00:52,228
If something isn't done,
I'll call out the whole Auxiliary.

20
00:00:52,394 --> 00:00:54,914
And the Junior Auxiliary.
We'll hold a meeting

21
00:00:55,080 --> 00:00:56,562
and see that it is...

22
00:00:56,723 --> 00:00:58,606
Yes, Spency? Who?

23
00:00:58,769 --> 00:00:59,726
The Governor?

24
00:00:59,892 --> 00:01:03,690
It's my building he jumping off!
And I'm up for re-election.

25
00:01:03,861 --> 00:01:06,016
What? Get Connell at the Bulletin.

26
00:01:06,187 --> 00:01:08,422
Why, he's liable to go
right past my win...

27
00:01:08,593 --> 00:01:10,315
- What was that?
- What?

28
00:01:10,557 --> 00:01:12,952
- The window. Something flew by.
- I didn't see anything.

29
00:01:13,124 --> 00:01:16,088
Don't stand there, you idiot.
Go and look. Open the window.

30
00:01:16,691 --> 00:01:18,927
Why did he have to
pick my building?

31
00:01:19,098 --> 00:01:22,894
Is there a crowd in the street?
Maybe he's caught on a ledge.

32
00:01:24,351 --> 00:01:26,710
- It must have been a seagull.
- A seagull?

33
00:01:26,876 --> 00:01:29,443
What's a seagull doing
around the City Hall?

34
00:01:29,603 --> 00:01:33,287
- That's a bad omen, isn't it?
- No, the seagull's a lovely bird.

35
00:01:33,854 --> 00:01:36,532
It's alright, Mrs. Brewster.
It's just a seagull.

36
00:01:36,700 --> 00:01:38,422
Nothing's happened yet.
I'm watching.

37
00:01:38,585 --> 00:01:41,264
Don't worry.
Leave it all to me.

38
00:01:41,431 --> 00:01:42,914
Spencer, I'll call you back.

39
00:01:43,437 --> 00:01:44,953
Hello, Connell?

40
00:01:45,521 --> 00:01:47,962
This is... What are you doing?
This is the Mayor.

41
00:01:48,128 --> 00:01:50,488
Yes, Mayor Lovett.
How many times you gonna call me?

42
00:01:50,854 --> 00:01:53,533
I've got everybody and his
brother and sister looking for him.

43
00:01:53,981 --> 00:01:55,577
See the box I'm running?

44
00:01:57,510 --> 00:02:00,110
"An appeal to John Doe.
Think it over, John.

45
00:02:00,276 --> 00:02:02,592
Life can be beautiful,
says Mayor.

46
00:02:02,762 --> 00:02:06,081
If you need a job, apply to
the editor and so forth..."

47
00:02:06,693 --> 00:02:09,497
Okay, Mayor, I'll let you know
as soon as I have something.

48
00:02:09,659 --> 00:02:10,890
What?

49
00:02:11,383 --> 00:02:12,979
Well, pull down the blinds.

50
00:02:13,269 --> 00:02:16,027
Went up to Miss Mitchell's house.
Boy, she's in a bad way.

51
00:02:16,556 --> 00:02:19,475
- Where is she?
- Supports her mother and two kids.

52
00:02:19,643 --> 00:02:22,117
- Did you find her?
- No. Her mother's worried.

53
00:02:22,290 --> 00:02:25,608
She said she was going on
a roaring drunk, the girl I mean.

54
00:02:25,778 --> 00:02:26,930
Go out and find her.

55
00:02:27,823 --> 00:02:30,468
The biggest thing I didn't tell ya.
Her old man's Doc Mitchell.

56
00:02:30,630 --> 00:02:33,869
He saved my mother's life
and wouldn't take money for it.

57
00:02:34,038 --> 00:02:36,079
Okay, Boss. I'll look for her.

58
00:02:39,732 --> 00:02:42,298
Holy smokes, Commissioner.
You've had 24 hours.

59
00:02:42,538 --> 00:02:46,382
Okay, Hawkshaw, grab a pencil.
Here it is again.

60
00:02:47,270 --> 00:02:50,668
About 5 foot five, brown eyes,

61
00:02:50,999 --> 00:02:52,594
chestnut hair...

62
00:02:53,043 --> 00:02:54,926
and as fine a pair of legs as...

63
00:02:55,972 --> 00:02:58,091
ever walked into this office.

64
00:03:00,702 --> 00:03:02,263
- Do you want to see me?
- No.

65
00:03:02,587 --> 00:03:04,948
I've had the whole Army
and Navy searching for you

66
00:03:05,112 --> 00:03:06,596
because it's a game we play.

67
00:03:06,756 --> 00:03:08,478
I remember distinctly being fired.

68
00:03:08,642 --> 00:03:12,484
That's right, but you have property
that belongs to this newspaper.

69
00:03:12,650 --> 00:03:13,928
- What's that?
- The letter.

70
00:03:14,095 --> 00:03:15,496
- What letter?
- The letter from John Doe.

71
00:03:16,621 --> 00:03:20,258
The town's in an uproar, we got to
find it. It's the only clue.

72
00:03:20,429 --> 00:03:23,155
- There is no letter.
- We'll get a handwriting expert to...

73
00:03:24,158 --> 00:03:25,721
- What?
- There is no letter.

74
00:03:29,572 --> 00:03:32,011
- Say that again.
- I made it up.

75
00:03:32,338 --> 00:03:34,015
You made it up.

76
00:03:34,182 --> 00:03:35,984
You said you wanted fireworks.

77
00:03:36,147 --> 00:03:38,988
Don't you know there are
9 jobs waiting for this guy,

78
00:03:39,155 --> 00:03:40,990
22 families want to
board him free,

79
00:03:41,159 --> 00:03:44,683
5 women want to marry him
and the Mayor's ready to adopt him?

80
00:03:45,008 --> 00:03:47,768
- Just called the morgue. A girl...
- Shut up!

81
00:03:50,021 --> 00:03:50,693
Ann! Why didn't you...?

82
00:03:50,863 --> 00:03:54,467
Only one thing to do, Hank.
Drop the whole business quickly.

83
00:03:54,632 --> 00:03:57,106
Run a story.
Say John Doe was in here,

84
00:03:57,277 --> 00:03:59,034
and is sorry he wrote the letter...

85
00:03:59,204 --> 00:04:01,928
Sure. He came in here and
I made him change his mind.

86
00:04:02,090 --> 00:04:04,849
"Bulletin Editor saves
John Doe's life." It's perfect.

87
00:04:05,017 --> 00:04:06,169
I'll have Ned write it up.

88
00:04:06,420 --> 00:04:09,181
- Ned, I got a story...
- Wait a minute.

89
00:04:09,508 --> 00:04:12,426
Listen, you great big
genius of a newspaperman.

90
00:04:12,594 --> 00:04:15,161
You came to shoot some life
into this dying newspaper.

91
00:04:15,322 --> 00:04:17,762
Well, the whole town's
curious about John Doe and boom!

92
00:04:17,927 --> 00:04:19,411
You're going to bury him.

93
00:04:19,571 --> 00:04:22,615
There's enough circulation in
that man to start an ink shortage.

94
00:04:22,779 --> 00:04:24,261
- In what man?
- John Doe.

95
00:04:24,424 --> 00:04:27,263
- What John Doe?
- Ours. The one I made up.

96
00:04:27,430 --> 00:04:29,312
Look genius. Now, look.

97
00:04:29,636 --> 00:04:33,353
Suppose a John Doe walked into
this office? What would you do?

98
00:04:33,525 --> 00:04:36,125
Find him a job and
forget the whole business, huh?

99
00:04:36,292 --> 00:04:38,332
Not me.
I'd make a deal with him.

100
00:04:38,497 --> 00:04:39,454
A deal?

101
00:04:39,620 --> 00:04:42,505
You don't drop a stunt to
sell papers like a hot potato.

102
00:04:42,667 --> 00:04:45,188
This is good for a couple of months.
Know what I'd do?

103
00:04:45,354 --> 00:04:48,877
Between now and Christmas,
when he jumps, I'd run a daily yawn.

104
00:04:49,042 --> 00:04:51,609
Starting with his boyhood,
his schooling, his first job.

105
00:04:51,770 --> 00:04:54,243
A wide-eyed youngster
facing a chaotic world.

106
00:04:54,415 --> 00:04:56,981
The problem of the average man,
all the John Does.

107
00:04:57,142 --> 00:05:00,347
Then comes the drama.
He meets discouragement.

108
00:05:00,511 --> 00:05:02,586
He finds the world has
feet of clay, his ideals crumble.

109
00:05:02,756 --> 00:05:05,322
What does he do? He decides to

110
00:05:05,483 --> 00:05:07,317
commit suicide in protest
against the state of civilization.

111
00:05:07,487 --> 00:05:09,962
He thinks of the river, but no.
He has a better idea:

112
00:05:10,134 --> 00:05:13,018
The City Hall. Why?
He wants to attract attention.

113
00:05:13,181 --> 00:05:16,704
He want to get things off his chest
and it's the only way to be heard.

114
00:05:16,870 --> 00:05:17,702
- So?
- So?

115
00:05:17,873 --> 00:05:20,153
So he writes me a letter
and I dig him up.

116
00:05:20,318 --> 00:05:23,077
He pours out his soul to me.
From now on we quote:

117
00:05:23,245 --> 00:05:25,161
"I Protest", by John Doe.

118
00:05:25,331 --> 00:05:27,804
He protests against
all the evils in the world.

119
00:05:27,976 --> 00:05:31,056
The greed, lust, hate, fear.
All of man's inhumanity to man.

120
00:05:31,224 --> 00:05:34,462
Arguments will start.
Should he commit suicide or not?

121
00:05:34,631 --> 00:05:37,232
People will write in,
pleading with him. But no, sir!

122
00:05:37,398 --> 00:05:38,915
John Doe will remain adamant.

123
00:05:39,082 --> 00:05:42,721
On Christmas Eve,
hot or cold, he goes, see?

124
00:05:44,976 --> 00:05:47,895
Very pretty, very pretty indeed,
Miss Mitchell.

125
00:05:48,064 --> 00:05:50,984
But would you mind telling me
who goes on Christmas Eve?

126
00:05:51,152 --> 00:05:52,588
- John Doe
- What John Doe?

127
00:05:52,755 --> 00:05:54,397
The one we hire
for the job, you lunkhead.

128
00:05:54,560 --> 00:05:57,799
Wait a minute. Let me get this
through this lame brain of mine.

129
00:05:58,009 --> 00:06:01,931
We hire someone who says they'll
commit suicide on Christmas Eve?

130
00:06:02,099 --> 00:06:03,329
Now you're catching on.

131
00:06:03,501 --> 00:06:06,421
- Who for instance?
- Anybody. Beany'll do.

132
00:06:06,589 --> 00:06:09,713
Why sure.
Who me? Jump off a...

133
00:06:09,877 --> 00:06:12,272
Anytime but Christmas.
I'm superstitious.

134
00:06:17,616 --> 00:06:21,584
Do me a favor. Go on out and
get married, have babies but...

135
00:06:21,745 --> 00:06:23,067
stay out of the newspaper business.

136
00:06:23,229 --> 00:06:25,463
Better get that story in hand.
It's getting late.

137
00:06:25,634 --> 00:06:28,280
You're supposed to be a smart guy.
If it was raining 100 dollar bills,

138
00:06:28,442 --> 00:06:31,042
you'd be looking for
a dime you lost someplace.

139
00:06:31,208 --> 00:06:33,681
Holy smokes. Wasting my time
listening to this mad woman.

140
00:06:33,854 --> 00:06:36,773
Look what the Chronicle's running
on John Doe. They say it's a fake.

141
00:06:37,022 --> 00:06:38,778
Why the no-good...

142
00:06:39,628 --> 00:06:42,102
"John Doe story,
amateur journalism.

143
00:06:42,275 --> 00:06:45,558
This is so phony, it's a wonder
anyone's taking it seriously."

144
00:06:45,722 --> 00:06:47,843
- What do you think of those guys?
- That's fine. That's fine.

145
00:06:48,008 --> 00:06:50,575
Now fall into their laps. Go ahead.

146
00:06:50,735 --> 00:06:53,050
Say John Doe walked in
and called the whole thing off.

147
00:06:53,221 --> 00:06:55,375
You know what that'll sound like.

148
00:06:55,545 --> 00:06:57,621
- That's all, Ned. Thank you.
- All right.

149
00:06:58,954 --> 00:07:00,950
Amateur journalism, huh?

150
00:07:01,120 --> 00:07:03,001
That bunch of sophomores.

151
00:07:03,164 --> 00:07:06,291
- I could teach them more...
- Boss! Get a load of this.

152
00:07:06,452 --> 00:07:07,936
- What?
- Look.

153
00:07:11,626 --> 00:07:12,617
What do they want?

154
00:07:12,788 --> 00:07:15,707
- They say they wrote the letter.
- Yeah, I wrote it, Boss.

155
00:07:15,915 --> 00:07:17,433
They all wrote the letter.

156
00:07:17,599 --> 00:07:21,317
Tell them all to wait.
One is your John Doe.

157
00:07:21,489 --> 00:07:23,485
They're desperate and will
do anything for a cup of coffee.

158
00:07:23,655 --> 00:07:26,380
Pick one and you can make
the Chronicle eat their words.

159
00:07:26,983 --> 00:07:28,214
I'm beginning to like this.

160
00:07:28,386 --> 00:07:30,951
If you ask me, Hank,
you're playing with dynamite.

161
00:07:31,112 --> 00:07:32,628
No, the girl's right.

162
00:07:32,795 --> 00:07:34,597
We can't let the Chronicle
get the laugh on us.

163
00:07:34,761 --> 00:07:36,402
We've got to produce
a John Doe now.

164
00:07:36,565 --> 00:07:39,370
Amateur journalism, huh?
I'll show those guys.

165
00:07:39,532 --> 00:07:42,452
Sure and there's no reason
for them to find out the truth

166
00:07:42,620 --> 00:07:44,900
because naturally
I won't say anything.

167
00:07:46,468 --> 00:07:49,434
- Okay, you get your job back.
- Plus a bonus.

168
00:07:49,596 --> 00:07:51,672
- What bonus?
- The bonus of 1,000 dollars...

169
00:07:51,841 --> 00:07:54,316
the Chronicle was going to
pay me for this little document.

170
00:07:54,488 --> 00:07:58,491
"I, Ann Mitchell, certify that the
John Doe letter was created by me..."

171
00:07:58,658 --> 00:08:00,000
- I can read. I can read.
- Sorry.
